# **Chapter 1: Introduction**

Why do intelligent, capable people sometimes act in ways that make us
scratch our heads?

Why does your coworker keep showing up late, even after being spoken to
about it? Why does your friend buy yet another "miracle" supplement from
Instagram while ignoring their doctor's advice? Why do some people pour
money into get-rich-quick schemes while disregarding sound financial
guidance? Or why do we cling emotionally to things we no longer need but
just can't let go of?

We've all seen behaviour that feels irrational, and if you work in
business, branding, or leadership, you see it daily. Understanding why
people behave the way they do isn't just fascinating, it's essential.

I've spent most of my life asking those kinds of questions. Not as a
psychologist, but as a marketer, first in radio broadcasting and
advertising, then as the founder of my own stations and agency.

My career accelerated in the '90s when I became General Manager of
**Telemedia Network Radio** in Toronto. At the time, we produced the
live radio broadcasts for the **Toronto Blue Jays** and **Toronto Maple
Leafs**. That role gave me a front-row seat to work with North America's
top ad agencies, representing some of the world's biggest brands.

That's where I had my first big realization: the ads that *worked*, that
truly moved people to act, weren't about facts. It wasn't the horsepower
that sold the car; it was how it made you feel behind the wheel. It
wasn't the memory capacity that sold the computer; it was what you could
*do* with it. And nobody ever chose a beer brand for the hops, it was
about identity, belonging, and story. The emotional message almost
always won.

At the time, I didn't know the science behind it. I just knew it worked.
As I built my business and helped others build theirs, I became
determined to dig deeper. If I could crack the code, not just the *how*,
but the *why*, I knew we could give our clients a serious edge.

That curiosity evolved into a lifelong quest. I devoured books, took
courses, and tested new ideas in the real world. Through years of trial,
error, and more than a few wrong turns, I came to a clear conclusion:

**Understanding human behaviour is essential in business.**

Whether you're trying to sell, lead, negotiate, or inspire, the better
you understand how people think and feel, the more effective you'll be.

As a new radio station owner in Barrie, Ontario, I was eager to put
these insights to use. I remember working with Ted, a local mechanic who
had just launched his own shop. For his first radio campaign, we didn't
talk about his equipment or pricing. Instead, we focused on his
personality. The ad featured a conversation with his wife, Banita, who
needed her car fixed, but Ted was always too busy helping customers
because their needs came first.

That was the *message.*

It wasn't about service bays or diagnostic tools. It was about values
and character. The ad worked. Ted's business grew from three bays to
twenty over the years, and the commercials ran for two decades, always
ending with the same line:

**"We fix anyone's car, except Banita's!"**

As our company expanded across the province with additional stations and
a marketing agency, I found myself giving countless presentations on
branding and behaviour, training our teams, advising clients, and
speaking at industry conferences. After nearly every talk, someone would
come up to me and say, "That makes so much sense. Can you explain more?"
This book is my way of saying yes.

What you will discover here isn't academic theory; it's practical,
real-world behavioural science rooted in areas such as:

**- Evolutionary psychology** explains how our brains are still wired
for survival, driving instincts to form tribes, seek safety, and chase
