## Logical Fallacies

After exploring Cognitive Biases---those intuitive shortcuts driven by
the Old Brain---we now shift focus.

Logical fallacies are a different kind of misfire. These aren't just
errors in instinct---they're **breakdowns in reasoning itself.** A
fallacy may sound logical at first, but collapses under closer
inspection.

Unlike biases, which operate mostly beneath awareness, fallacies often
arise in the New Brain's domain. They show up when it rushes to justify
an Old Brain impulse, defend a belief, or win an argument. Sometimes
it's unconscious---the smaller gear struggling to keep up with the big
one. Other times, fallacies are used deliberately, as persuasive tools
that rely on flawed logic.

Either way, they signal the **mental transmission slipping out of
sync.**

Learning to spot fallacies is like feeling when your cognitive clutch
isn't fully engaged. It lets you downshift into clarity, slow down, and
assess whether the reasoning truly holds up.

Let's explore the most common types---so you can recognize them in real
time and shift out of faulty logic before it takes you somewhere you
don't want to go.

## False Cause Fallacy

Also known as *post hoc* reasoning, the false cause fallacy occurs when
we assume one event caused another simply because they happened around
the same time. This instinct often stems from the Old Brain's tendency
to spot patterns and jump to conclusions.

This is where the New Brain must shift into manual mode and ask: *"Could
something else be at play?"* That one question can open the door to
deeper reasoning, helping us avoid oversimplifying and arrive at a more
accurate understanding of cause and effect.

*[Example:]* Imagine someone notices that ice cream sales
and violent crime rates increase during the summer months. Jumping to
the conclusion that eating ice cream causes violent crime is a classic
false-cause mistake. The real factor might be the warmer weather, which
encourages more people to be outside, leading to increased ice cream
purchases and more opportunities for conflict.

## Fundamental Attribution Error

The **fundamental attribution error** occurs when we blame external
circumstances for our own questionable actions, yet attribute others'
missteps to their character. This reflex is driven by the Old Brain's
need to preserve our self-image.

When we make mistakes, the "thin-skinned" Old Brain quickly signals the
New Brain to rationalize---to protect how we see ourselves and how we're
seen by others. Admitting fault risks shaking our sense of competence
and our social standing, both of which are deeply tied to survival
instincts.

At the first sign of personal blame, the Old Brain's gear spins faster,
while the New Brain struggles to engage the clutch, slowing things down
with honesty, logic, and introspection.

*[Example:]* If another driver cuts you off, you might yell
*"Asshole!"* at them and happily give them the finger. But if you
accidentally cut someone off because you were momentarily distracted,
you don't see yourself as a terrible person---it's just an innocent
mistake.

## Red Herring Fallacy

A Red Herring strategically introduces irrelevant details that distract
from the core issue we are trying to tackle. Imagine your Old Brain
yelling, "Look over here!" just as your New Brain tries to concentrate
on the real problem. This diversion can create confusion, making it
challenging to address what truly matters. Instead of clarity, we become
entangled in a web of distractions that can lead to misdirected efforts
and wasted time. Recognizing a Red Herring is crucial; it enables us to
refocus our attention on the pressing issues that require our immediate
action and thoughtful consideration.

*[Example:]* Ask a politician about environmental policies,
and they pivot to talking about job creation. The shift in topic is
deliberate--- an attempt to divert attention from the actual question.

## Bandwagon Fallacy

This fallacy cleverly takes advantage of our Old Brain's deep-seated
urge for belonging and group acceptance to fit in---after all, if
everyone else is doing it, it must be right...right? It makes us
especially vulnerable to following the crowd, even when it might not
serve our best interests. Recognizing this tendency can help us make
better decisions guided by genuine needs instead of group pressure.

*[Example:]* "Everyone is investing in cryptocurrency, so it
must be a good idea," or a politician saying, "Everyone agrees with my
plan."

## Straw Man Fallacy

The Straw Man approach is a rhetorical tactic that distorts or
oversimplifies another person's argument, making it significantly easier
to dismantle or refute. This method often involves misrepresenting the
opposing viewpoint, which allows the user to attack a weakened or
exaggerated version of that argument rather than addressing the actual
position.

*[Example:]* "You say we should have less homework, so you
must want students to learn nothing!" It twists a moderate suggestion
into an extreme position that's simple to attack.

## Slippery Slope Fallacy

The Slippery Slope argument suggests that a seemingly minor change can
trigger a domino effect, ultimately resulting in severe and often
disastrous consequences. This concept preys upon the Old Brain's
inherent fear of the unknown, bypassing rational reasoning and jumping
to extreme conclusions.

*[Example:]* "If we allow students to use calculators, soon
they won't know how to do basic math."

## Appeal to Emotion Fallacy

This tactic targets our feelings directly rather than providing solid
evidence. It leverages the Old Brain's emotional pull while ignoring the
New Brain's need for data or reason.

*[Example:]* "Think of the children!" as a way to shut down
any counterargument without addressing the facts.

## False Dilemma Fallacy

Also known as the "either/or" fallacy, it corners you into picking
between two options, even though more choices might exist. It's a neat
trick that exploits our instinct to make quick judgments.

*[Example:]* "You're either with us or against us." In
reality, there are often many ways to support---or disagree---without
taking an extreme stance.

## Guilt by Association Fallacy

The guilt by association fallacy crops up when we accept or dismiss an
idea because of **who is linked to it** rather than **what the idea
actually says**. Our Old Brain's hard‑wired tribal radar scans for
friend‑or‑foe signals; if a proposal or person even *smells* connected
to a distrusted group, the reflex is to shove them outside the campfire
ring---no questions asked.

But the New Brain's job is to pause and probe: *"Is the claim itself
sound, regardless of its source?"* By separating people from
propositions, we prevent rash judgments that can starve us of good
information or steer us into bad decisions.

***[Example:]*** A start‑up pitches a recycling technology
at a municipal forum. When council members learn the founder once
interned at a petroleum company, they reject the plan outright---"Big
Oil fingerprints all over this!" Yet the tech's carbon footprint data
were independently audited and beat every alternative on the table. The
council's snap decision protected their image but torpedoed a solution
that actually advanced their sustainability goals.

Recognizing that the New Brain often deploys logical fallacies to
justify decisions already made by the Old Brain helps us think more
critically and communicate more ethically. These aren't just slips in
logic---they're usually attempts to rationalize gut-level choices after
the fact. By spotting this pattern, we can shift into manual mode, slow
down our reasoning, and challenge flawed arguments---both our own and
others'. This awareness also sharpens our branding and messaging,
letting us craft compelling narratives without relying on manipulation
or faulty logic.

## Cognitive Dissonance

You've likely felt that uncomfortable mental tension when your actions
don't quite match your values. That's cognitive dissonance---your mind's
alarm system for internal conflict. It kicks in when the **Old Brain
makes a fast, emotional decision**, and the **New Brain struggles to
justify it**.

It's like our two brain gears suddenly **grind against each other**,
creating psychological friction. The Old Brain, which craves harmony and
quick resolution, can't tolerate this misalignment for long. To get the
mental machine running smoothly again, we instinctively seek ways to
reduce tension.

Sometimes, we compartmentalize our beliefs, tucking conflicting ideas
into separate corners of the mind so they don't clash. However, when
conflict becomes unavoidable, we face a choice: either update our
beliefs or attempt to explain them away.

In theory, the healthiest solution would be to revise one or both
conflicting ideas. But that's hard work. So, more often, we **slip back
into automatic mode**, and the **New Brain shifts into rationalization
gear**. It starts telling a story that makes our actions make
sense---even if that story is built on shaky logic. This is **special
pleading** in action: bending reason to fit the narrative we want to
believe.

Cognitive dissonance shows just how tightly the Old and New Brain are
linked---and how often the New Brain's role is less about reasoning and
more about repairing the emotional aftermath of a snap decision.

**Signs of Cognitive Dissonance:**

- Feeling uneasy before making a decision, as the smaller gear tries
to resist the momentum set by the larger gear.

- Justifying or rationalizing actions after the fact, with the smaller
gear turning to provide a narrative that fits the Old Brain's
instinctive choice.

- Experiencing guilt or regret when the smaller gear recognizes a
mismatch between action and belief.

- Feeling like a victim, the smaller gear struggles to resolve
inconsistencies in a way that preserves the Old Brain\'s positive
self-image.

- Conforming to social pressures even when they conflict with personal
beliefs, as the large gear pushes for acceptance and safety, while the
smaller gear tries to justify the compromise.

Understanding cognitive dissonance can be advantageous in marketing and
business. Introducing new ideas and concepts that resonate with the Old
Brain can alleviate dissonance, prompting a subconscious appreciation
for the efforts made.

## Victimhood Reconsidered

As we've explored, cognitive dissonance arises when an individual's
actions contradict their self-perception. For example, someone who sees
themselves as "good" may feel mental tension if their behaviour suggests
otherwise. To ease this discomfort, the New Brain often alters the
narrative, portraying the individual as a **victim of circumstance** or
the actions of others. This helps preserve the Old Brain's positive
self-image.

In this moment, the **larger gear** keeps spinning, reinforcing the
belief, "I am good," while the **smaller gear** engages in
rationalization---working to justify behaviours that contradict that
self-concept. **Unless we deliberately shift into manual mode**, the New
Brain often goes along for the ride, supporting the Old Brain's
preferred storyline.

Unfortunately, many people default to victimhood as a coping mechanism.
It allows them to reduce internal conflict without confronting
uncomfortable truths. But if your product or service empowers
individuals to **consciously shift gears**, accept accountability, and
plan for change, it can strengthen the New Brain's ability to develop
healthier strategies going forward.

Encouraging people to take ownership of their actions---and to envision
their desired future state---can be a powerful branding strategy. It
aligns your message with personal growth, resilience, and
transformation. That's why so many motivational speakers and authors
have built careers around this very insight.

## Why All This Matters in Branding

Understanding the errors in thinking reviewed above isn't just
interesting trivia---it's essential for connecting with your audience on
a deeper level.

**- Build Trust:** By avoiding logical fallacies and recognizing
mental shortcuts, your messaging remains credible, giving the New
Brain fewer reasons to stall out.

**- Influence Decisions:** Leveraging cognitive biases ethically helps
engage the Old Brain first, then smoothly shift into New Brain
validation, guiding your audience toward choices they can feel *and*
justify.

**- Enhance Engagement:** Addressing moments of cognitive dissonance
gives customers the chance to pause, reflect, and shift into manual
mode, deepening emotional connection and brand loyalty.

## Wrapping It Up

By now, you've seen how easily the Old Brain can lead us astray---with a
