# **Chapter 14: Brand Value Canvas**

**"People do not buy goods and services. They buy relations, stories,
and magic."**

Seth Godin, All Marketers Are Liars (2005)

## Applying the Divided Brain to Your Brand

At this point, you might be wondering:

**"Okay, I get it. I now understand how people think and choose. But how
do I actually apply this to my brand, startup, or business?"**

You're in the right place.

You've seen how the Old Brain and New Brain shape every choice we make.
But insight alone won't move the needle---what matters is how you
*apply* that understanding to create a brand that resonates, connects,
and converts.

That's where the **Brand Value Canvas** comes in. It's a hands-on
framework that brings the Divided Brain metaphor to life. It helps you
clarify and distill your **Brand Promise**---the single, unshakable idea
you **want to own in your customer's mind.** This isn't just about
positioning or messaging. It's about aligning your brand with the core
emotional and rational triggers that drive behaviour. And what do I mean
by brand value?

## Value Is Perceived, Not Measured

In marketing, "value" isn't determined solely by utility or cost---it's
a story we tell ourselves. As Vice-Chairman of Ogilvy UK, Rory
Sutherland often argues that **perception usually trumps objective
reality.**1^ A product's actual function may remain constant, but our
experience of it can be dramatically altered by branding, context,
design, or even the story we associate with it.

Consider how coffee in a plain white styrofoam cup tastes different from
the same coffee served in a sleek, ceramic mug. Or how paying \$6 for a
bottle of water at a luxury hotel feels acceptable, while the same water
at a gas station might seem overpriced. In each case, the actual product
remains unchanged, but the perceived value has shifted.

This is why branding is not window dressing. It's a framing device that
shapes how people experience your offer.

The **Brand Value Canvas** is built on this foundation: that *real
value* lives in the overlap between what you offer and what your
audience finds meaningful, distinctive, and worth noticing.

## What Is Your Brand Promise?

Also known as your value proposition or unique selling proposition, your
**Brand Promise** is the mental shortcut that tells people why they
should choose you. It's the first message that engages their emotional
instincts and the last thing they recall before making a decision. A
strong Brand Promise shifts your audience into gear, starting with the
Old Brain and then syncing with the New.

To truly move someone, your promise must include all three of these
components:

**1.** **Emotional Resonance (Old Brain)**

We know the Old Brain responds first. Your promise must **spark
feelings**---security, admiration, confidence, inclusion, empowerment.
Emotion is what grabs attention and gets the large gear turning. Without
it, the rest of the system comes to a halt.

**2. Rational Validation (New Brain)**

Once the Old Brain is engaged, the New Brain steps in. This is where
logic, evidence, and reassurance come into play---features,
testimonials, guarantees, or specifications. These help the smaller gear
catch and turn smoothly, allowing the mind to justify what the heart
already wants.

3\. **Distinctive Uniqueness (New/Old Brain)**

To stand out, your promise must clearly demonstrate what sets you apart
from the competition. Whether it's a unique experience, innovation, or
market positioning, differentiation ensures your brand doesn't get lost
in the noise. If it's challenging to differentiate in our
hyper-competitive world, your second option can be *to claim a specific
benefit or idea first*; you lodge it in the Old Brain's memory before
competitors even arrive. We'll explore this principle of first-to-mind
positioning in more depth shortly. For now, consider it a way to keep
your brand's transmission running smoothly and prevent emotional energy
from slipping into neutral due to confusion with lookalike brands.

Brand Promise Stool

When you bring together *emotion, logic, and differentiation*, you
create a balanced and persuasive foundation---like a three-legged stool.
Remove one leg, and the whole structure becomes unstable.

Your Brand Promise should be **clear, concise, and
compelling**---ideally just one sentence or even a few words. While it
doesn't need to be your public-facing tagline, it should guide your
positioning, messaging, and internal alignment at every turn.

## How the Brand Value Canvas Guides You

In the section that follows, you'll learn how to fill out each quadrant
of the Canvas:

**- Customer Insights**: Pinpoint Needs, Pains, and Desires to uncover
the emotional triggers and rational requirements that matter most.

**- Brand Responses**: Translate those insights into tangible
Solutions, Pain Relievers, and Rewards---your promise in action.

**- Differentiation**: Evaluate each promise point for uniqueness,
ensuring you stand out in a crowded market.

**Following these steps will crystallize a Brand Promise that cuts
through the noise---something your customers will instantly recognize
and readily defend.**

You'll be able to create brand messaging that:

**- Feels right to the gut and heart** (Old Brain).

**- Makes sense to the mind** (New Brain).

**- Stands out from the crowd** (Differentiation).

The following two pages illustrate two versions of the Brand Value
Canvas. The first is a print version that you can download
([paullarche.com/resources/](http://paullarche.com/resources/)) or
replicate. It is designed for use in a workshop environment with
employees and stakeholders. The second version is available through our
online app
([paullarche.com/brandvaluecanvas](http://paullarche.com/brandvaluecanvas)),
which is free to use. This may be more convenient if you fill it out
yourself. All instructions are available on the app by clicking the "?"
icon. You can print or save your results.

## Instructions for Using This Canvas in Workshop

**Preparation:**

- Replicate a large-scale version of the canvas. A PDF can be
downloaded at
[paullarche.com/resources/](http://paullarche.com/resources/)

- Gather sticky notes, markers, and pens.

- Invite relevant employees, stakeholders, and, ideally, customers.

**Step-by-Step Guide**

## Step 1: Understanding Your Customer

This first phase is about discovery. Each participant contributes
insights by writing sticky notes under the following sections:

**- Needs (Rational/Tangible):** What specific objectives, goals, or
problems does your customer want to achieve by buying your product or
service? Write one need per sticky note.

**- Pains (Rational and Emotional):** What frustrations, concerns,
fears, or costs (time, money, energy) affect your customers? Record
each pain individually and **rank them in order of relevance**.

**- Desires (Emotional/Intangible):** What hidden emotional
drivers---such as aspirations, identity, or connection---motivate your
audience? Capture each desire on a sticky note and **rank them in
order of emotional importance**.

**Timing:** Allow 15 minutes for individual brainstorming. Then do the
following:

1\. Have participants place their sticky notes in the respective
customer sections.

2\. The facilitator consolidates overlapping or duplicate ideas.

3\. As a group, agree on the top 3--5 insights in each category and
place them in ranked order.

## Step 2: Your Brand\'s Response

In this phase, the team maps your brand's response to the customer
insights.

Each participant writes sticky notes for:

**- Solutions:** How does your brand meet each customer's rational
needs? What features, specifications, and functionality do you offer?
Align each solution directly with its corresponding need.

**- Pain Relievers:** How does your product or service alleviate the
pains identified? Each should be matched to a pain point. **Rank each
effectiveness from 1 (low) to 5 (high).**

**- Rewards:** How does your brand meet emotional desires or create
positive experiences? Align each reward with its matching desire.
**Rate each reward from 1 to 5 for emotional impact.**

**Timing:** Allow another 15 minutes for this exercise. Then:

1\. Have participants place sticky notes in the Your Brand section
across from each corresponding customer insight.

2\. The facilitator consolidates duplicate or similar answers.

3\. As a group, discuss and rate each response's effectiveness on
a scale of 1 (weak) to 5 (excellent).

**Place these sticky notes in their respective sections.**

## Step 3: Evaluate Uniqueness

Now, assess how distinct your brand's responses are compared to those of
your competitors. For each Solution, Pain Reliever, and Reward, score
your brand's uniqueness on a 1 to 5 scale:

1\. Common -- Found everywhere

2\. Slightly different -- Minor edge

3\. Noticeably different -- Moderate differentiation

4\. Highly unique -- Difficult to replicate

5\. One-of-a-kind -- Nearly impossible to copy

On a sticky note, write the uniqueness score beside the corresponding
attribute under the Uniqueness column.

There was a time when being unique was easy. Think of a small town
hardware store. But today, it may be challenging to find your
differentiator.

**The Challenge of Standing Out in a Sea of Sameness**

In today's hyper-competitive world, especially in tech and Software as a
Service (SaaS), differentiating your brand can feel nearly impossible.
Features blur together, benefits sound the same, and every brand shouts
into the void.

If it's tough to articulate what truly sets you apart, it's time to
conduct a competitive brand audit. Take a close look at how your
competitors position themselves. You might discover they're not
emphasizing attributes you *also* offer---attributes that matter to your
customers.

**This presents a powerful opportunity:** you can be the *first* to
**claim that point of difference** in the market.

In the language of *Positioning: The Battle for Your Mind* (2001), the
classic book by Al Ries and Jack Trout:

**"It's better to be first than it is to be better."**2^

Why? Because the first brand to occupy a mental position creates
familiarity. And familiarity is everything to the Old Brain.

The Old Brain---the fast, automatic part of our mind---values
**efficiency, repetition, and consistency**. It doesn't want to
re-evaluate every choice. Once it forms an association (e.g., "this
brand equals fast support" or "this software is the simplest"), it tends
to solidify it.

This is why being first to claim the position matters so much. It's
not just about attention; it's about ownership. The first brand to
occupy a position becomes the "default," and from then on, any
challenger has to work much harder to override what's already filed
away. The Old Brain resists change because **change burns energy**.
Unless there's a compelling reason to reassess, the brain will stick
with what it already knows and trusts.

In other words, **positioning is path-dependent**. If you're the first
to plant your flag, you don't just get there early---you make it harder
for anyone else to move in after you.

If this is the case, consider the following uniqueness scoring on a 1 to
5 scale:

1\. All competitors promote it

2\. Most competitors promote it

3\. Some competitors promote it

4\. Very few or one competitor promotes it

5\. No competitor promotes it

## Step 4: Calculating Your Brand Value Score

To quantify the value of your findings:

1\. Add each attribute's effectiveness score (Step 2) and uniqueness
score (Step 3).

2\. Focus primarily on high-scoring attributes in **Pain Relievers**
and Rewards---these engage the Old Brain and are key to brand
loyalty.

3\. Competing in that area may not be easy if an attribute scores low
in uniqueness (2 or below).

**Tip:** Use high-scoring **Solutions to Needs** as rational
backup---the information the New Brain needs to justify the Old Brain's
emotional decision.

## Step 5: Develop your Brand Promise

Hopefully, by this step, your Brand Promise will begin to crystallize
and become apparent. If there is still ambiguity, you should revisit
your scores and have an honest and open debate. Essentially, you want to
craft only one Brand Promise, so take your time if it does not
become self-evident.

Keep the following top of mind:

1\. A Brand Promise can be one sentence or just a few words.

2\. Your Brand Promise does not necessarily become your hook or
tagline, but all your marketing and positioning should be grounded in
the Brand Promise.

3\. Brand promises rarely change and take time and concerted effort to
become effective. Unfortunately, many companies decide to change their
promise (see Consistency Builds Trust in Chapter 10) before it is
anchored to their target customers.

Here are some compelling Brand Promises from companies you know
well---each one a clear, memorable pledge that emotionally resonates
(Old Brain) and carries rational ballast (New Brain):

**1. Nike**

**- Promise:** "If you have a body, you are an athlete."

**- Tagline:** "Just Do It."

**- Old Brain:** Empowers everyone to see themselves as athletes.

**- New Brain:** Performance‑driven footwear and apparel for all
levels.

**2. Coca‑Cola**

**- Promise:** "To inspire moments of optimism and uplift."

**- Tagline:** "Open Happiness."

**- Old Brain:** Sparks joy, nostalgia, and togetherness.

**- New Brain:** Consistently refreshing flavour, reliable quality
worldwide.

**3. Airbnb**

**- Promise:** "Belong anywhere."

**- Tagline:** "Belong Anywhere."

**- Old Brain:** Promises connection, adventure, and the comfort of
home.

**- New Brain:** A global network of vetted listings with easy booking
and support.

**4. Trader Joe's**

**- Promise:** "Unique products, great prices, and friendly service."

**- Tagline:** "Your Neighbourhood Trader Joe's."

**- Old Brain:** Feels like a personal, community‑centric grocery
discovery.

**- New Brain:** Carefully curated items, competitive pricing, and
helpful staff.

**Practical Tips:**

- Clearly define next-step actions, responsible team members, and
deadlines directly on the canvas.

- Revisit and revise the canvas regularly---especially when launching
a new campaign, entering a new market, or refreshing your brand.

## Wrapping it Up

Completing the Brand Value Canvas isn't just an exercise in
strategy---it's a way to decode what truly drives your customers. By
mapping emotional motivators, rational validators, and your unique
differentiators, the canvas helps you build a brand that speaks to both
gears of the mind: the instinctive Old Brain and the analytical New
Brain.

It brings clarity, collaboration, and action to your branding efforts,
ensuring that your message not only makes sense but also evokes a
genuine emotional response. When your brand promise is aligned with how
humans are wired to think and choose, it's like shifting into the right
gear at the right time---smoother traction, greater momentum, and far
less resistance.

